President Obama has announced his intent to nominate Judith Fergin as Ambassador to the Democratic Republic of Timor-Leste. Fergin is currently Consul General in Sydney, Australia, and has served in various diplomatic roles in countries such as Singapore, Indonesia, and Germany. She holds a Bachelor of Arts degree from Smith College and Master's degrees from the University of Virginia and the Industrial College of the Armed Forces of the National Defense University.

Additionally, President Obama has announced his intent to appoint Suzan Johnson Cook as Ambassador-At-Large for International Religious Freedom at the Department of State. Cook is the Founder and President of Wisdom Worldwide Center and has served as the Senior Pastor of Bronx Christian Fellowship Baptist Church in New York City. She holds multiple degrees, including a Doctor of Ministry.

Felice D. Gaer has been appointed as a member of the U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom. Gaer is the director of the Jacob Blaustein Institute for the Advancement of Human Rights of the American Jewish Committee and has extensive experience in human rights advocacy. She has also served as chair of the U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom and as an Independent Expert on the UN Committee against Torture.

Lastly, William J. Shaw has been appointed as a member of the U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom. Shaw is the Immediate Past President of the National Baptist Convention, USA, Inc. and Pastor of White Rock Baptist Church in Philadelphia. He has held various leadership positions in religious and community organizations and has received numerous awards for his work.

President Obama expressed his gratitude for the expertise and commitment these individuals will bring to their roles and looks forward to working with them in the future.